posts.subject: Who to believe?
posts.body:
https://archive.vn/5HRNA

Buzzfeed overestimates their own cred here, but their observations as to the difficulty of separating truth from fiction are correct. 

But here is a key phrase: "noting that authoritarian societies are further along the path to a full infocalypse than the US is."

Over the long term, misinformation gets weeded out in free societies. That's fact. And it's proven by countless academic experiments.

But just what does one do when the only "sources" of news are littered with biases? Weeding out that fiction becomes much more difficult.

So here's my advice to those concerned with misinformation: "Discover anyone on your staff who spins a story with political, gender, or alphabet activism - FIRE THEM IMMEDIATELY." Before they forever cost you your reputation....

Firing for deeds is actually a concession. If it were up to me all leftists, feminists, childless, unmarried, or alphabets would be automatically disqualified from news generation. All of em - just fucking noise. They don't count. Their "reality suppression field" disqualifies them.
